{
  "answer": "The matla (opening couplet) of Allama Iqbal's poem in *Bang-e-Dara Part 2*, chapter 4 addresses the \"worldly stage\" (*bazm-e-jahan*), conceding that its spectacles (*hungamay*) were enchanting or grand (*dilkash*), while claiming that sorrow inevitably afflicted its onlookers.[^1]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, ch. 4 (\"Yoon to ae bazm-e-jahan! dilkash thay hungamay teray\"), [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/04-yoon-to-ae-bazm-e-jahan-dilkash-thay-hungamay-tera/translation/#p-6fed75).  \n**Original transliteration:** *Yoon to ae bazm-e-jahan! dilkash thay hungamay teray*.[^2]\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, ch. 4 (\"Yoon to ae bazm-e-jahan! dilkash thay hungamay teray\"), [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/04-yoon-to-ae-bazm-e-jahan-dilkash-thay-hungamay-tera/transliteration/#p-988c94).",
